knowledge_graph.title: Cetaceans
knowledge_graph.description: Cetacea is an infraorder of aquatic mammals belonging to the order Artiodactyla that includes whales, dolphins and porpoises. Key characteristics are their fully aquatic lifestyle, streamlined body shape, often large size and exclusively carnivorous diet.

related_questions.question: What defines a Cetacea?
related_questions.snippet: Cetacean is the collective noun used to describe all 90 species of whales, dolphins and porpoises. The word cetacean has its origins in Latin (Cetus) referring to a large sea creature and Greek (Ketos) meaning whale or sea monster.

related_questions.question: What animals are in the Cetacea order?
related_questions.snippet: (whales, dolphins and porpoises) Taxonomy classifies whales, dolphins and porpoises as the Order of Cetacea (known commonly as cetaceans) and divides this group into two suborders: Mysticeti (baleen whales or mysticetes – approximately 14 species) Odontceti (toothed whales or odontocetes – approximately 75 species)
